{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:13:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18724"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18724"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0,0.04,0,0.79]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62575"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10558"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENormal sperm cell production requires precise coordination between hormones from the anterior pituitary gland and factors produced within the testes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the hormonal regulation of spermatogenesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FSH causes testosterone secretion from Leydig cells","Testosterone is the only hormone needed for sperm production","Both LH and FSH directly stimulate Sertoli cells","FSH and LH bind directly to developing spermatocytes","LH acts on Leydig cells while FSH targets Sertoli cells"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key hormonal control involves \u003Cstrong\u003ELH acting on Leydig cells while FSH targets Sertoli cells\u003C/strong\u003E. Luteinising hormone binds to Leydig cells located in the testicular interstitium, triggering testosterone production. Follicle stimulating hormone binds to Sertoli cells, which then provide crucial support for developing sperm cells and produce proteins that concentrate testosterone within the seminiferous tubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFSH causes testosterone secretion from Leydig cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Leydig cells respond to LH, not FSH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETestosterone is the only hormone needed for sperm production\u003C/strong\u003E - Both FSH and testosterone are essential\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth LH and FSH directly stimulate Sertoli cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Only FSH acts on Sertoli cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFSH and LH bind directly to developing spermatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - These hormones act via supporting cells rather than directly on developing sperm cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis dual control system ensures proper development and maturation of sperm cells through the coordinated actions of both hormones on their specific target cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Follicle stimulating hormone acts on Sertoli cells which provide structural and nutritional support for developing sperm cells.","Luteinising hormone stimulates testosterone production by Leydig cells in the testicular interstitium.","Both FSH and high local testosterone concentrations are required for complete spermatogenesis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62575"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18724"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62575"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T00:02:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T00:03:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"c